. Baranger Co., 520 Examiner Blag.,\nSan Praucisco, CaL; 802 Title Insurance\nBid*.. Lee Angeles, Cal.: 226 Pos'.-Intel\nllgehcer Bldg., Seattle, Wash.\nBUSINESS CHANCE\u00bb\n17 ROOM rooming house, steam heat\nfree; cheap rent; terms. Pacific Agen\ncy, 102 First avenue south. _\nSALES AGKNCY is available for easy\nselling, strong repeating office line.\nPermanent business opportunity. Small\ninvestment required for stock. Casey,\n4 730 McGraw, Detroit\nADVERTISE\u2014Rate book mailed free*\nStandard Advertising Agency, 25- Vic\ntoria, St. Louis.\nFOR S\u00c4LE \u2014Soft drink stand and lunch\ncounter. Bargain if taken at once.\nBox 5 4. Cit y.\nLARGE Manufacturing corporation\nwants capable men to open branch of\nfice and manage salesmen; $300 to $2,\n000 necessary; handle your own money.\nExclusive rights; patented article, mon\ney making possibilities unlimited. Will\npay expenses to Baltimore if you qual\nify. Address Mr. Clemmer, Salesman\na.ger, 603 N. Eutaw St., Balt imore, Md.\nMcCRAY refrigerator; Hobert electric\ncoffee grinder; Dayton electric scale;\nDetroit auto scale; Dayton computing\nmeat slicer; 12-foot Peerless display\ncounter; 16-foot Sherrer display coun\nter; roll top desk and chair; American\ncash register; small safe; glass show\ncase; oil tank; cheese cutter; 50 feet\nof shelving and bases. Inquire Mrs. G.\nH. Ross, 715 Park^ Drive, ^ity.\nFOR SALE\u2014Small business in splendid\nlocation, Great Falls. Apply box 169.\nT ribune\nFOR SALE\u2014Millinery stock and fixtures.\nEstablished business; good location.\nBargain to cash buyer. Box 168, Tri\nbune.\nFOR SALE OR TRADE\u2014One first class\ncafe in a good town; no competition.\nAddress Box 23.',. Denton. Mont.\nFOR SALE\u2014Good grocery business, auto\ndelivery, garage, also living rooms.\nThis property and business can be\nhandled for about $8.000, or will take\na live partner. Box 164, Tribune.\nHOTELS, grocery stores and trades.\nInterstate Realty, 208% Central.\nlegal advertising\nnotice of closing registra\ntion.\nNotice is hereby given that the regis\ntration books for the registering of vot\ners, for the annual city election for the\ncities of Great Falls and Belt, and the\ntowns of Cascade and Neihart.. to be\nheld on Monday, April 4th, 1921, will\nclose on Thursday. February 17th, 1921,\nat 5 o'clock p. rn. of that day. Persons\nwho failed to vote at the general elec\ntion November 2nd, 1920, to bo enabled\nto vote at such election must re-register,\nothers to vote must register on or before\nthe above closing date. To be eligible\nto vote a person must be a citizen of\nthe United States, a resident of the\nstate of Montana for one year, and of\nthe city or town for six months prior\nto the day of election. If you are not\nregistered you cannot vote. Electors of\nthe city of Great Falls must register\nat the office of the county clerk, at the\ncourthouse, in Great Falls, Montana.\nElectors of Belt, Cascade and Neihart\nmay register before a notary public,\njustice of the peace or deputy registrar\nin their respective city or town. If you\nare not registered you cannot vote.\nDated Jan. 4th, 1921.\nJOHN E. MO RAN,\nCounty Clerk and Ex-Officio Registrar.\nNOTICE TO STOCKHOLDERS.\nThe annual meeting of the stockhold\ners of the First National Bank of Great\nFalls, Montana, will be held in the bank\ning rooms of said bank between the\nhours of 10 a. m. and 4 o'clock p. m. on\nTuesday, January 11, 1921, for the pur\npose of electing the board of director\u00ab\nfor the ensuing year and for the trans\naction of any other business that may\nproperly come before said meeting.\nDated at Great Falls, December 11,\n1&20.\nW. A. BROWN. Cashier.\nnotice of closing registra\ntion.\nNotice is hereby given that the reg\nistration books for the registering of\nvoters for the primary nominating elec\ntion for officers of the city of Great\nFalls, Montana, to be held on Monday,\nMarch 21st, 1921. will close on Thurs\nday, February 3rd, 1921, at 5 o'clock\np. m. of that day. Persons who failed\nto vote at the general election Novem\nber 2nd, 1920, must re-register, all oth\ners not previously registered to be en\ntitled to vote at such primary must be\nregistered on or before the above clos\ning date. If you are not registered you\ncannot vote. To be eligible to vote at\nthe city election, a person must be a\ncitizen of the United States, a resident\nof the state of Montana, for one year\nand of the city six months prior to the\nday of election. Registration office\nopen from 9 o'clock a. m. until 5 o'clock\np. m. every day except Sundays and\nholidays, at the office of the county\ncierk in the courthouse, Great Falls,\nMontana.\nDated January 3rd, 1921.\nJOHN E. MORAN,\nCounty Clerk and Ex Officio Registrar.\nnotice of closing of regis\ntration.\nNotice is hereby given thai the reg\nistration books for the registering of\nelectors for the election of trustees at\nthe annual school election, in School\nDistrict No. 1, of Cascade county, Mon\ntana, to be held on Saturday, April\n2nd, 1921, will close on Tuesday, Febru\nary 15th, 1921, at 5 o'clock p. m. of that\ndate. To be eligible to vote at such\nelection, a person must be a citizen of\nthe United States, a resident of the\nstate of Montana for one year and of\nCascade county for 30 days prior to the\ndate of election. Registration office\nwill be open from 9 o'clock a. m. until\n5 o'clock p. m. each day except Sundays\nand holidays, at the office of the coun\nty clerk at the courthouse, Great Falls,\nMontana. If you are not registered\nyou cannot vote.\nDated January 4, 1921.\nJOHN E. MORAN,\nCounty Clerk and Ex Officio Registrar.\nKaffir boys at the age of 12 are edu\ncated in the use of the javelin.\nD\nWAN\nD\nD.\nD\nAIRKETo\n\u00ceNANOAL M\nTHE WEEK SN BUSINE\nBy The Tribune.\n=3\nu\nNew York. .fan. 8.\u2014The first week of j\nthe new year was characterize.] by a j\nmarked increase of activity at higher\nprice's for stocks and bonds, although j\nthe credit situation continued somewhat\nstrained and the reinvestment demand j\nwas comparatively light.\nSentiment, among traders and the pro-\nfessional element was more hopeful but j\ndue account was taken of the important j\nchanges stili in progress in the commod\nity markets and in general lines of trade\nand inquiry.\nGains in the stock list were more sub\nstantial among the speculative issues j\ncomprising the industrial and special\nvarieties, this same condition applying j\nto the bond market, in which convertible\nrails developed pronounced strength.\nRelease of January interest and divi\ndend payments was without effect upon\nthe money market, call loans holding\nfirm at 7 per cent, while time accommo\ndations were meager, apart from some\nheavy western demand.\nBankers are conferring regarding cred\nit extensions and new loans to Europe\nand South America, but the outcome is\nsaid to be contingent upon a partial re\nadjustment of present unsuccessful con\nditions.\nDEMAND FOR MONTANA LAND\nEXPECTED TO DEVELOP SOON\nMontana, whatever other difficulties it\nmay have experienced, does not now\nhave to face the results of an artificially\nstimulated land boom, and our cheap\nland is what is expected to bring about\na return of prosperity far quicker, per\nhaps, than will be the case in the middle\nwest, says the January bulletin letter\nof the Great Falls National bank. It\ncontinues:\nIt is not improbable that there will\nbe, before long, a good demand for land\nin this state for farming arid stock grow\ning at the low prices that have already\nbegun to prevail, while such land will\nnot be taken over unless the purchasers\nare financially able to stock it or farm it\nproperly. In other words there appears\nto be grounds for expecting a substantial\nmovement of land for investment and\nnot for speculation and Montana may\nprofit greatly from the misfortunes of\nUs eastern neighbors.\nAnother reason for a more confident\nfeeling in this state is the seeming cer\ntainty that the cost of operation on\nfarms will be far lower this year than\nfor some time past. Farm labor is al\nready much cheaper and more efficient,\nwhile costs of all materials, food stuffs\nand machinery either have shown sub\nstantial declines or must do so shortly.\nAlso the weather up to the end of the\nyear was idoal for wintering stock and\nfor preparing ground for cropping, enab\nling many farmers to do a lot of this\nwork themselves at their leisure instead\nof making hired help necessary.\nOil Field Developments.\nEvery new development reported in\nthe oil producing district of Fergus\ncounty tends to confirm the belief that\nan important reservoir of extremely high\ngrade petroleum has been tapped. So\nphenomenal have been the drilling results\nthere that interests in the oil world\npromises iater this year to center in\nMontana and a great amount of pros\npecting in other localities in the state\nmay be looked for. Already leases on\nhundreds of thousands of acres of pros\npective oil lands in many counties have\nbeen taken and spring will undoubtedly\nsee an invasion of drilling rigs. The\nexpected rapid development of another\nof Montana's natural resources should\nbe a further factor in the return of pros\nperity.\nThe Wool Situation.\nWool growers are still awaiting a nor\nmal consumers' buying market to start\na movement to the mills of wool held in\nstorage, and there appears to be little\nprospect of good prices until there is\nsome basis for starting business and\nvalues are allowed to work to a level\njustified demand and supply. It has\nbeen predicted freely that the new ;>ear\nwould see further cutting in clothing\nprices to clear up stocks, and that this\nwould start a buying movement by 'he\nmills. There have been reports of so ne\nsales of Montana wools on a basis of\nfrom SO to 35 cents, but such sales have\nbeeu limited in number.\nBANK CLEARINGS SHOW GAIN\nFOR WEEK ENDED SATURDAY\nGreat Falls bank clearings for ^the\nweek ended Saturday were $2,080,501,\nan increase of $702,570 over the previous\nweek, and an increase of $3,188 over the\nfigures for the corresponding week of\n1920.\nREFUNDING LEGISLATION\nTO AFFECT LIBERTY BONDS\nBy Irving Whitehouse Co.\nThe market is sensitive to every fac\ntor which concerns the country's general\nprosperity and quotations or prices in\nvariably anticipate and discount the real\nization or postponement of expected fu\nture developments. Credit cannot sus\ntain itself, it must be based on revenue.\nThe financial power of the state rests\nupon the economic development of the\npeople and will be proportional to it.\nEverything we do is the inevitable result\nof all that has gone before, but. in the\nvernacular of describing market move\nments, quotations and price tendencies\nusually reflect expectations before they\nare galvanized into life.\nFuture Is Uncertain.\nThe greatest factor which will in\nfluence the Liberty bond market during\nthe next six mouths will be not only the\nrumored prospect but the terms under\nwhich any new funding or refunding is\nagitated or likely to be undertaken by\ncongressional authorization. Any legis\nlation which means an increase in the\npresent debt or interest rate will be a\nblow at the market value of bonds in\ngeneral and particularly the outstanding\nLiberty bonds which are now just begin\nning to show their ability to stand alone.\nIt will not be so much a question of the\nrate of interest us the extent to which\nany new loan is made tax-exempt that\nwill affect the market.\nNo doubt the financial policy of the\ntreasury will remain unaltered until the\nnew administration takes office next\nMarch. At that time and not until then,\nwill it be safe to hazard a guess as to\nwhat the future course of the Liberty\nbond market will be.\nOn Favorable Terms.\nIn the meantime, however, it seems\nreasonable to believe that investors will\nhave had an opportunity to purchase the\nobligations of the l.'iiited States on more\nfavorable terms than will again be\nsi hie for many years to come.\nThe following are a few of the\nbond quotations:\nAm. Tel. Te. tj's\nCanadian go'vs 5\" s 1921\nCanadian gov's \u00e4's 192\u00d6\nCanadian gov's 5\"s 1931\nC. B. Q. joint 4' s 1921\nCh. Mil. St. I'. Hy. 4's.. 1925\nMontana Power 5's 15143\nI n. Kingdom B G 1 5l'\u00bb's 1921\nAnaconda 6's 3929\npos\nlive\"\n90 V 2\n99 <8\nK,S'/2\n8<i%\n96%\n77 1\nS2 \"s\n98\nS3 >2\nBUSINESS BASICALLY SOUND\nIS VERDICT AFTER SURVEY\nS.t Louis. Jan. 8.\u2014The condition of\nbusiness iu the United States is basic\nally sound, and fear for the welfare of\ncommercial America is due principally to\na \"state of mind,\" a natural consequence\nof the war.\nThis is the gist of an economic^ sur\nvey conducted by the Mississippi alley\nassociation, and announced at headquar\nters here. Questionnaires sent to busi\nness men, bankers, agriculturists and\neconomic students in the \"'valley\nbrought thousands of replies.\nThe underlying thought in the an\nswers is that the present business de\npression is caused by the \"consequent\nand necessary deflation of the inflation\"\nand the universal demand for lower liv\ning costs. This condition was augmen\nted, numerous replies stated, by an era\nof extravagance in buying, without con\nsideration for the future.\nTo the question, \"what additional sys\ntem of credits should he inaugurated\n(if any) to release money when urgent\nly needed in our agricultural and indus\ntrial centers\" many replied that profits\nof the federal reserve board should be\nmade available for farm credits, and the\nestablishment of loug time credits to\nfarmers.\nSome recommended establishment of\nmore farm loan banks.\n\n\n\n\ni\ni\ni\nSUGAR IMPORTATIONS JUMP\nOVER FIGURE OF LAST YEAR\nWashington, Jan. 8.\u2014The amount of\nsugar imported into the I'nited States\nlast November exceeded by near 20,000,\n000 pounds the amount imported during\nthe corresponding month of 1919, accord\nins to a report of the bureau of foreign\nand domestic commerce. A departure\nfrom the usual trend of the cane sugar\ntraffic was noted in that Cuba contrib\nuted li s- than one-half of th total in\nthe month, the figures being ,'<..117\nout of a total of 4^.\",143.337 f ounds as\"\ncompared with 400,788,959 out of a total\nof 414.709,949 pounds in November,\n1919.\nAnother reversal of usual conditions in\nthe foreign market noted in the report\nwas the nearly complete cessation of tern\nimportations from Argentina for the\nmonth. In November. 1919. 1,'\u00ee07.S7!)\nbushels were imported while in the same\nmonth- last year the United States took\nbut 40.100 bushels of the crop.\n\"Wheat exports, however, took a sp\u00fcrt,\nmounting to a total of 20.00.\".147 bush\nels shipped to all countries against the\nNovember, 1919, figure of 15.1 Hi,107\nbushels.\nGreat Britain was the heaviest buyer\nwith an aggregate of 4,789.212 bushels.\nIncreased values of ron and steel in\nthe foreign market were reflected in\ntonnage shipped compared with prices\nreceived for November exports.\nIn November, 1919, 21.429 tons were\nexported, valued at $771.301. In the\nsame month, last year. 19.929 tons ex\nported were valued at $734,440.\nCRUDE OIL PRICE IS CUT\nBECAUSE DEMAND REDUCED\nPittsburg, Pa.. Jan. 8.\u2014The price of\nPennsylvania crude oil, on which is based\nthe price of other oiis in this country,\nwas today cut from $6.10 a barrel to\n$5.75 a barrel. This is the first reduc\ntion in crude oil for n number of years\nand is brought about, the princ'pa\u00ee pur\nchasing agencies said, by a decreased\ndemand.\nNews of Business\nand of Industries\nSanta Ana. Cal., Jan. 7.\u2014 Reductions\nin lumber prices, averaging 25 per cent\nand effective next Monday were an\nr.ounced by dealers here Saturday.\nDetroit. .Tan. 8.\u2014The Liberty Motor}\nCar company, which has been operating\nwith a decidedly curtailed staff, an\nnounced Saturday that it would re-em\nploy several hundred addition men Jan\nuarv 17.\nMilwaukee, Jan. 8.\u2014An order for\n.$1,000.000 worth of gas engines for the\nUnited States Steel Corporation to be\ninstalled at its South Chicago subsid\niary, has been obtained by the Allis\nChalmers company it was reported Sat\nurday.\nPortland, Jan. 8.\u2014 Local wheat and\nflour shippers Saturday were offering\nshipments at the rate of $15 a ton to\nthe United Kingdom and $15 to Medit\nerranean ports following declines from\n$18 a ton in the shipping board rate\nthis week.\nAllentown. Pa., Jan. 8.\u2014The New\nJersey Zinc company at Palmerton Sat\nurday announced a 10 per cent cut in\nwages and the elimination of an 8 per\ncent bonus system, effective January\n15. The plant will return to full oper\nation.\nSpokane, Jan. 8. -An advance of 2 Ys\ncents a pound in the wholesale price of\nbeef was made effective Saturday by\nlocal packers. An increase in the whole\nsale price of pork cuts to two cents was\nmade Friday. Smoked meats also have\nadvanced 1 to 2 cents a pound, packers\nannounced. Livestock market condi\ntions were ascribed as the cause.\nMinneapolis, Jan. 8.\u2014Shop employes\nof the Minneapolis. St. Paul <Sr Sault t-'te.\nMarie railroad have been placed oh a\nfive day week, it was announced Sat\nurday. About 1.400 men are affected.\nW. H. Bremer, president of (he\nMinneapolis St. Louis railroad esti\nmated that 1.250 employes have been\nlaid off by that company over the en\ntire system since September 1.\nThe Great Northern railway also is\nreducing- its forces whereven possible,\nMr. Martin, vice president, said.\nIn the ear of Dionysius, a cavern near\nNeapolis, the faintest whisper is audible\nat a great distance.\nNew York Maurikdt\nfinancial.\nNew York, Jan. 8.\u2014The stock market i\nSaturday opened with a modest show of j\nstrength, some buying and short cover- j\ning evidently being prompted by the en-\ncouraging observations of Governor\nHarding of the federal reserve board.\nTrading had not proceeded beyond the j\ninitial stage, however, before fresh weak-\nness developed in the shippings, steels,\nand oils, with Atlantic Gulf, Crucible j\nSteel and Mexican Petroleum as the j\nchief objectives.\nDeclines of two to six points in these j\nissues soon had their effect on the gen- j\neral list, where other popular shares for- j\nfeited one to three points. Nominal ral-\nlies ensued under cover of a sharp rise\nin General Asphalt and International\ni Paper but these were not sustained,\ni many material losses being registered at\ni the heavy close. Sales amounted to\n,500.000 shares.\nNews which bore more or less pertln\ni ently on market values included the\nj statement that one million tone of ship\nping have been withdrawn from trade\nby the shipping board, opening of bids\ni by the government for the sale of 56.000,\n000 pounds of copper and announcement\nthat one of the largest independent steel\nproducing companies had written off\ni $5,000,000 in its Inventory to get down to\na \"replacement basis.\"\nConsidering the turn into the New\nYear, the clearing house statement\nshowed few important changes for the\ni week, aside from a contraction of slight\nly more than $54,000,000 in actual loans\nI and discounts and an increase approxi\nI mating $50,000,000 in net demand de\nposits.\nThe bond market was dull and heavy,\nreflecting the reversal in stocks. Libertv\nissues forfeited part of their recent gains\nand foreign flotations also eased. Total\nsales (par value) $6,150,000. Old United\nStates bonds unchanged on call for the\nweek.\nmoney.\nNew York, .Tan. 8.\u2014Prime mercantile\npaper 7\u00ae^ 8 per cent. Eire demand\n347; cables 349.\nNew York, Jan. 8.\u2014Prime mercantile\npaper unchanged. Exchange steady.\nSterling\u2014Unchanged.\nFrancs\u2014Cemand 5.94; cables 5.96.\nBelgian francs\u2014Demand 6.25; cables\nG.27.\nGuilders, lire and marks\u2014Unchanged.\nGreek marks\u2014Demand 7.45.\nNew York exchange on Montreal 14' s\nper cent discount.\nLIBERTY BONDS.\nNew York, Jan. 8.\u2014Liberty bon