siness as may properly come before\nsaid meeting.\n(Signed) t. f. adams, Sec\n^Dated Dec. 28. 1920.\nChicago Market\ntiRAIN ANO PROVISIONS.\nChicago, Jan 8. A bulge during the\nlast hour on moderate buying and a lack\nof offerings gave wheat a good undertone\nSaturday and the market closed firm\nwith prices showing a net gain of IVic to\n2Vic over the previous close with March\n$1.73% to $1.74, and May $1.6Q% to $1.66^;\ncorn was unchanged to bic nlgher oats\nunchanged to Vic down while provisions\nwere lower for pork and lard but firmer\nfor ribs.\nWheat developed a strong undertone\nand advanced sharply after a weak start,\ndue to persistent buying to remove hedges\nagainst export sales.\nThe British commission was not m tue\nmarket but the continent was a good buy\ner and sales of 750,000 bushels were re\nported to Germany and Italy.\nCoarse grains were slightly easier 0^ r 'V\nbut rallied with wheat. Trade was light\nand mostly of a local character, Minne\napolis reported 25,000 bushels corn sold\nto Baltimore, the first business from that\nmarket so far.\nOats were dull practically all day, while\nprovisions averaged higher on scattered\nbuying and light offerings.\nPrices of futures follow:\nWheat.\nMarch\u2014Open, $1.72; high, $1.74%; low\n$1.71%; close, $1.73%.\nMay\u2014Open, $1.65%; high, $1.67Vs; low,\n$1.64% close, $1.66%.\nCorn\nMay\u2014Open, 74%; high, 75%; low, 74%;\nCl Jul'y\u2014 Open, 75%; high, 76; low, 75%;\nclose, 75%.\nOats.\nMay -Open. 48%; high, 48%; low, 48%,\nV 'July\u2014 Open, 47%; high. 48%; low, 47%;\nclose, 48.\nchicago cash market.\nChicago, Jan. 8.-Wheat No. 3 mixed\n51.68% 1.71%; No. 2, $1.76.\nOats. No. 2 white 47*4<&4ii, No. 3\nwhite 40 46\nRye, not quoted.\nBarley. 60\u00a988.\nTimothy seed. $6. to.\ni Clover seed, $16^ $23. pi\nPork nominal. Lard $lo.50. Ribs,\n$11.25@$12.\nBITTER AN I> EGOS.\ni Portland, Jan. 8.\u2014Butter .steady. Ex\njtra cubes 42043; parchment wrapped\n1 prints, box lots 49c; cartons 50c; half\ni box lots